Group-by and agg.

Group-by partitions the rows by one or more keys. And agg applies one or more aggregate functions to each of those groups. Both are lazy, so execution waits for an action.

Inside agg, you use the aggregate functions from the library — count, count-distinct, sum, average, min, max, collect-list, and collect-set. And you can alias each result, so for example, agg of sum of amount, aliased as total.

Now, what happens under the hood? Group-by triggers a shuffle — it is a wide transformation. But before the shuffle, Catalyst does a map-side partial aggregate. That is the very same map-side-combine win you saw earlier with reduce-by-key. And it is one more reason to prefer the dataframe group-by over hand-rolled R-D-D grouping — you get the efficient combine for free.
